Furthermore, the United Nations shows that the country’s population has been increasing, on annual basis, by more than 1.1 million people for the past ten years.
As the year ends, more than 800,000 young people joined the job market.  At least two out of eight of these job seekers have either a university degree or a tertiary level diploma. Unfortunately, Covid-19 has been a major challenge for those trying to enter the job market.





Between 2018 and 2019, the economy added 68,400 formal jobs: 46,100 in the private sector and 22,300 in national and county governments. Sadly, the government has noted that private sector employment, often the first point of call for job seekers, was already in decline before the arrival of the coronavirus.
According to the Economic Survey, new employment opportunities in the corporate and private sector in general fell by a record 20 per cent: from 57,600 to 46,100. Thousands of Kenyans have already been rendered jobless and ongoing tough financial environment would only trigger more bankruptcies, redundancies, and layoffs.
Generate sufficient jobs
Rather than acknowledge the inability of the economy to generate sufficient jobs for millions of its young people, the government makes an outrageous claim. In the Economic Survey, it is estimated that in 2019 alone, more than 780,000 individuals were effectively absorbed into informal sector as well as self-employment.



