 In other words, the government assumes all these individuals were gainfully employed, even though it cannot tell us in which sectors. Granted, the informal sector is important, but it is infeasible that it could be employing that many additional people year after year.
This is nothing but an attempt by the government to gloss over a worsening employment crisis by making baseless estimates.
It is not surprising that the country’s leadership, including the President is not interested in this reality and are unconcerned by the sheer magnitude of this mounting national crisis.
But this is worth emphasising. Every year, 800,000 Kenyans are joining the workforce without any real chance of getting a job and the situation is worsening.
Let’s briefly examine the President’s response in the BBI, which is a top priority of his government and a majority of the governors. The President wants to expand the Executive and the Parliament by creating additional positions.
It is estimated that it costs about Sh52 million to support a single Member of Parliament. On the other hand, the Economic Survey shows that a Kenyan employed in the formal sector earns Sh65,000 a month.



