Street protests
There is a growing admission that despite protests and opposition, the President and Raila will pursue their objective of amending the Constitution. They may have their way but when the rubber meets the road, Kenyans would no doubt express themselves more forcefully, and in far less pleasant ways.
This is inevitable given the financial difficulties that many families face today. The Treasury will soon abolish Covid-19 tax relief measures and will raise new taxes to fund the referendum and these changes. When that happens, the pain would be felt by both the passionate proponents of the BBI and those that oppose it.
The President continuously justifies his push for an expanded Executive on the need to accommodate bitter un-conceding political rivals, and to preserve peace.
For poor, jobless and hopeless Kenyans, the message is clear: take to the streets in protests, toy with treason like the swearing in of the so-called People’s President in Uhuru Park, and stay defiant. Perhaps then, someone would want to listen to your concerns and do the right thing.
